Company Culture & Psychology.\
\
Creating and nurturing an engaging work environment that people are
excited to come to every day & are prideful to talk about with their
friends & family can be a difficult thing to accomplish.\
\
I'm always trying to find new ways to engage & motivate my team.\
\
These are the structures that have worked for me (in no particular
order) \...\
\
1. That special feeling. Everyone wants to feel valued. Praise growth &
small successes, too. Extra effort is worth acknowledgment.\
\
2. Opportunity. Clear pathways to growth are important. Most folks are
not interested in staying at an entry-level position and want to know
there is a future for them available.\
\
3. Incentivization. If the company succeeds, so should the team. Create
personal incentives as well as team-based incentives. This motivates
team members on a personal & enterprise level to promote
forward-thinking, increased QC, & reduction of a lackadaisical
attitude.\
\
4. Discipline. If the ball gets dropped, the team needs to understand
the cost & consequences of their actions to reduce the exposure to
repeating these instances.\
\
5. An environment that reflects the culture. All companies are
different, & the look & feel of the workplace needs to reflect the
culture. Sometimes ditching the sterile colors & lifeless walls by
adding a little color, texture, decor, or music can make massive changes
in the way your team members feel about their environment.\
\
6. Empowerment to lead & innovate. No one likes to be micro-managed.
Empower your teams to find the best way to do something instead of doing
it for them. 9/10 times you give team members a task, they will find the
easiest way to do it. Rely on them to become the masters of their
domain - let go of the control & let them bloom into confident problem
solvers & leaders. They will respect you more & have far more pride in
what they do.\
\
7. Approachability. One of the biggest issues I've seen in leadership is
the lack of approachability. Organizations are essentially organisms. An
organism needs to adapt and evolve to survive the ever-changing world
around it, and it does this by receiving feedback from its stimuli and
making appropriate changes to suit the changing environment. Your
organization\'s stimuli are its team members. If they're not comfortable
providing you feedback on the good, bad & ugly, then small issues can
fester, growing into outcomes that could have ultimately been avoided.\
\
8. Clear communication & concise instruction. No one likes the unknown.
Being able to come into work, knowing what you have to do for the day,
with clear instructions & goals are important to reducing stress levels.
These clear & narrow bands of focus also allow team members to innovate
on current processes to improve efficiency. Being spread too thin breeds
stress, inaccuracy, & stifles innovation.\
\
What do you do to motivate, increase engagement, & cultivate a great
company culture?
